        {
            "id": "intro_loops",
            "elements": [
                {
                    "type": "heading",
                    "content": "Functions with Loops",
                    "properties": {
                        "level": 1
                    }
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "Functions can use loops to process multiple items, perform repeated calculations, or build results step by step."
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "Combining functions and loops makes your code more organized and reusable."
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "id": "basic_loop_function",
            "elements": [
                {
                    "type": "heading",
                    "content": "Functions with For Loops",
                    "properties": {
                        "level": 2
                    }
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "Remember `for` loops? You can use them inside functions to process each item in a list, one by one."
                },
                {
                    "type": "code",
                    "content": "def print_items(items):\n    for item in items:\n        print(item)\n\nfruits = [\"apple\", \"banana\", \"cherry\"]\nprint_items(fruits)",
                    "properties": {
                        "language": "python",
                        "output": "apple\nbanana\ncherry"
                    }
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "The parameter `items` receives the list. The `for` loop goes through each item and prints it. This makes the function work with any list!"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "id": "accumulating_results",
            "elements": [
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "A common pattern is to **accumulate** (build up) a result in a loop and then return the final value."
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "Start with an initial value  → Loop through items → Update the value each time → Return the final result."
                },
                {
                    "type": "code",
                    "content": "def sum_numbers(numbers):\n    total = 0\n    for num in numbers:\n        total = total + num\n    return total\n\nresult = sum_numbers([5, 10, 15, 20])\nprint(result)",
                    "properties": {
                        "language": "python",
                        "output": "50"
                    }
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "`total` starts at `0`. The loop goes through each number and adds it to `total`. After the loop finishes, the function returns the accumulated `total`."
                }
            ]
        },
        {
